Today is National Suicide Awareness Day. The National Suicide Prevention Lifeline (@800273TALK) offers free, confidential crisis counseling 24/7/365 - and you don‚Äôt have to be in crisis to call. #SPM20 #NotAlone

September is National Suicide Prevention Awareness Month‚Äîa time to share resources and stories in an effort to shed light on this highly taboo and stigmatized topic. We use this month to reach out to those affected by suicide, raise awareness and connect individuals with suicidal ideation to treatment services. It is also important to ensure that individuals, friends and families have access to the resources they need to discuss suicide prevention. NAMI is here to help.

https://www.nami.org/get-involved/awareness-events/suicide-prevention-awareness-month

Welcome to the NWPHS team Pete!

I‚Äôm Pete Carlin and I‚Äôm glad to be a part of the Northwest Passage mission and team! I have been teaching traditionally for about five years and non-traditionally for much of my adult life through museums, rehabilitation facilities, and various guest residencies. My licensure is in Communications (English Language Arts) and I received my Masters degree in Education from St. Mary‚Äôs with a focus on technology. I‚Äôm originally from New Rochelle, NY, went to college in Pittsburgh, then DC for eight years, but moved here from Los Angeles 10 years ago with my wife and two daughters. We live in the west metro area of Minneapolis with our dog Ozzie and cat Snoopy. I like movies, theatre, reading, almost anything outside - particularly Ultimate frisbee and fishing - except for maybe winter. Let‚Äôs learn how to have fun (despite the masks) and make the world a better place together.

post_text:
Please welcome one of our newest staff member -

My name is Drew Joerger, and I am the newest Social Studies Advisor at Northwest Passage High School. I grew up in St. Louis, Missouri, but have since lived in cities including Chicago, Seattle, and Denver. I studied history and visual communications at Loyola University Chicago and recently graduated from the University of Minnesota's M.Ed. program. I love learning about the different expressions of culture and ways humans interact with each other and their environments.

I am an avid traveler, and I especially enjoy exploring mountains, lakes, and rivers while backpacking, biking, paddling, and skiing. This summer I had the privilege of hiking in the Sawtooth Mountains of Idaho and kayaking the Namekagon River in Wisconsin. I love cooking for my friends and family, listening to live music, and spending hot summer nights on my porch with my partner and our pet rabbit, Napoleon Bunaparte. I am very excited to grow with our learning community here at NWPHS, and look forward to the adventures to come.

To the Northwest Passage High School Family:

Now that graduation is over and we have properly congratulated and honored our seniors, I want to take a moment to hold space for the memory of George Floyd and thetrauma that is engulfing Minneapolis. These are difficult times filled with sadness, anger and confusion, but just know that whatever you are feeling we are here to support you. Please feel free to reach out to any of us via email or phone (Facebook is not the right forum) and we will honor your brave conversations. Be safe, enjoy your weekend and let us know how we can help.

Hi! I just wanted to tell you how touched I am that the teachers are out congratulating seniors! I just watched Reggie from my apt building receive his cap and gown, I watched the teachers dance and sing (you killed it, guys! Lol! I don't have any kids that go to your school, but I wanted to reach out anyway! The love was felt during a really unloving time...... You are truly the people that touch lives..... I'm sure they will never forget what you guys have done for them!

Sincerely
Sonia DeFede

post_text:
This week's Why Wednesday comes from 2019 graduate Lucy. "Middle schoolers and high schoolers, hear me out. I was just like you - a kid lost in the school system with only dread for the next year, but that's when I found out about Northwest Passage High School. Call me crazy or cliche, but I love this school - the teachers, the trips, the projects! If you want a school where you don't have to feel like a little fish in a big tank then take a look at nwphs.org. Trust me it's worth your time!"

Lucy recently graduated from Anoka-Ramsey CC in the 911 Dispatcher program. She just got a job with Allina (Mercy Hospital) as a security dispatcher.

So proud of you Lucy!

post_text: Who is ready to start Distance Learning tomorrow? One of the most common tips about working/studying at home is to have a dedicated space for your work time. When you go to that space, you'll know it's not the same spot on the couch or bed where you are used to playing video games or watching youtube. But what if, like most of us, you don't have a separate room, desk or even a section of a table that you can dedicate to your school stuff? Get creative! Cate made a sitting/standing desk from her dresser. What can you come up with?

post_text:
Good Morning NWPHS Fam!

You probably have a lot of questions right now. Staff will be contacting students and families today to get the details of what you need in your Distance Learning Kit and answer as many of your questions as we can.

If your student does not have a cell phone or access to email, please contact the student's advisor first and then school if needed at 763-862-9223.

Distance Learning Kits may include things like; a Chromebook, charger, books, printed homework, and other educational resource needs, plus any of your personal stuff.

Distance Learning Kits will be available for pick up tomorrow, Tuesday, March 24th from 12:30am - 5:30pm from your student's building. If you are unable to pick up the care package during this time, please contact your students advisor or call the school.

Stay healthy & Stay safe!

post_text:
We are overdue in welcoming our newest staff members! First up is special education teacher, Sharon Booth.

I have been a Special Education Teacher since 2013, mainly at the high school grade level, with an emphasis in English, Reading, Writing, and Time Management. My goal has always been to teach and guide our youth while helping them to learn and understand the importance of being successful in their academics so they will make positive contributions to their community and society.

I like being creative and helping students to expand their creativity which is why I am both excited and grateful for the opportunity to be involved in Project Based Learning and to be part of the staff at NWPHS.

post_text:
It's Why NWPHS Wednesday!

Why I enjoy working in Headwaters:

Being an educator in my 21st year at NWPHS, I am enjoying being a part of creating and implementing the new Headwaters program for our incoming 9th grade students. It is very exciting to be a part of a very dynamic team of educators who are continually looking for ways to improve how we teach and implement project based learning at our school. I believe the Headwaters program is making a difference for our new 9th grade students and we are seeing great successes. Being a part of something innovative and dynamic has made this one of my favorite years of teaching. -Theresa Boisjolie

post_text:
Another new member of our paraprofessional team: Terry Daugherty!

I have recently moved from Michigan and am feeling very fortunate to find such an amazingly progressive learning environment to work in! For the past 19 years I have worked with a MoCI Special Ed program and I have a love of woodworking so being able to combine these experiences and skills into the NWPHS project based learning family is very exciting for me!

post_text:
2019-2020 New Staff Introductions continue! We are very excited to welcome a new advisor for our Graduation Focus Program: Krista Bertelson

I have been working in outdoor education and experiential learning since 1994. I went into "the classroom" at a K-12 Montessori environment in Florida and then drifted into training educators on customized learning in recent years. I've been working across the nation with many innovative schools assisting districts in their transition to a leaner-focused environment. I am excited to be back working with learners and am honored to join the team here.
